\subseteq \{\bar{X}:q(\bar{X})\}$ ( or $p = \{\bar{X}:q(\bar{X})\}$ or $\{\bar{X}:q(\bar{X})\} \subseteq p$ ) is true in $A$ by
$$p(\bar{t}) \leftarrow body$$
for each $p(\bar{t}) \in A$ .
\end{enumerate}
Set $A$ is an \emph{answer set} of $\Pi$ if it is an answer set of the set introduction reduct of $\Pi$ with respect to $A$ .
\end{definition}
\begin{example}
[ Set introduction rule ] \label{e25}
Consider a program $P_9$ from Example \ref{e20} .
The reduct of this program with respect to $A_1 = \{q(a)\}$ is $\{q(a).\}$ and hence $A_1$ is an answer set of $P_9$ .
The reduct of $P_9$ with respect to $A_2 = \{q(a),p(a)\}$ is $\{q(a). \ p(a).\}$ and hence $A_2$ is also an answer set of $P_9$ .
There are no other answer sets .
\end{example}
The use of a set introduction rule $p \subseteq S \leftarrow body$ is very similar to that of choice rule $\{p(\bar{X}) : q(\bar{X})\} \leftarrow body$ of \cite{nss02} implemented in Clingo and other similar systems .
In fact , if $p$ from the set introduction rule does not occur in the head of any other rule of the program , the two rules have the same meaning .
However if this condition does not hold the meaning is different .
An $\mathcal{A}log$ program consisting of rules $p \subseteq \{X:q_1(X)\}$ and $p \subseteq \{X:q_2(X)\}$ defines an arbitrary set $p$ from the intersection of $q_1$ and $q_2$ .
With choice rules it is not the case .
We prefer the set introduction rule because of its more intuitive reading ( after all everyone is familiar with the statement `` $p$ is an arbitrary subset of $q$ ' ' ) and relative simplicity of the definition of its formal semantics as compared with that of the choice rule .

